<br>
I am not particularly interested in nit-picking the proposed design (altho I will if wanted). <br>
If I may quote myself from earlier in the thread:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>       That is irrelevant tho, Particular failure mechanisims are unimportantant. Common mode failures, software bugs, LH2 system failures, etc. all can lead to loss of the vehicle, and total catastrophe.<br>
<br>
You seem to be adopting the same &quot;Unsinkable Titanic&quot; mindset that the nuclear industry did ...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It is basic engineering practice to assume that absolute failure ~will~ occur and what is the result.<br>
<br>
In a case like Yucca Mountain, the design of the repository is such that, if all engineered systems fail, then due to the natural barriers the public will be protected. (Hopefully)<br>
<br>
In the case of a rocket launcher (chemical, nuclear, laser, whatever) you MUST assume complete failure.<br>
<br>
A disintegrating high pressure LH2 turbopump can (and has) tear apart the booster. When your are travelling 13,000 miles per hour through the air and something like this happens, it is Goodnight Irene.<br>
<br>
As NASA says:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>    Concern #3: High energy components used in aerospacecraft powerplants, such as high temperature and pressure combustion chambers, turbopumps, and plumbing can fail, not only damaging the components in the vicinity, but also fail with enough energy to cause catastrophic collateral damage to the vehicle.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And don't bother coming up with a tightly engineered rube-goldberg mitigation procedure for this problem. It is only one of a zillion potential problems inherent in rocketry, which is only compounded by the special characteristics of a nuclear engine.<br>
<br>
---------------------------<br>
<br>
Lets be clear about one thing.<br>
<br>
It is only the risks involved in using such a craft at sub-orbital speeds that concerns me. I am simply echoing (and concurring with) the policy of NASA ~AND~ the policy of the United Nations, not to use such a vehicle within the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
There is trivial risk in transporting fresh uranium fuel into high orbit. A gas-core nuclear rocket assembled and fueled there could travel to Mars in a matter of weeks. <br>
<br>
It is reusable and could open a commuter line to the planets.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
