Not quite. You provided entirely inadequate response to most issues. Mostly arm-waving claims to unsubstantiated future hopes. <br>
<br>
It reminds me of the old joke:<br>
<br>
--<br>
Q: How does an economist get out of a deep hole?<br>
A: First, he assumes a ladder...<br>
--<br>
<br>
You are off by a factor of 10 in some characteristics.<br>
Your response to generic issues that affect all types of rockets was essentially a non-response. (ie. A loose access panel on the exterior of the rocket can tear loose, resulting in a cascading aerodynamic structural failure - resulting in the craft tumbling and tearing itself apart.)<br>
<br>
BTW - your 300 MWt per square meter cooling requirement is way off. It is more like 800 MWt per square meter. Since you describe a future &quot;design goal&quot; of 100 MWt/M^2, you will have instant Melt City.  (as an aside, the UV photo-lith glasses are being engineered to be transparent at the SPECIFIC freqs, not a super-perfectly-transparent-at-every-wavelength-and-high-ionizing-radiation-and-extreme-temperature-and-intense-neutron-flux mega glass.<br>
<br>
And this is just for UV photons!<br>
The TOTAL radiant flux thru the glass is 8,000 megawatts per square meter. (Thats equal to the electrical power output of EIGHT atomic power plants!) And the entire glass &quot;bulb&quot; is ten times that area. <br>
<br>
That means that an area of the glass tube equal to a standard TV screen must perfectly transmit the radiant power equal to the electrical output an entire atomic power plant. The power used by 1,000,000 homes!<br>
<br>
And that is multiplied about 80 times for the whole glass &quot;bulb&quot;<br>
(and there are 7 of these engines)<br>
<br>
And this transmitted radiant power must be absorbed by flowing hydrogen propellent in a space you could bridge with your arms. Even with an added absorber (which would be ejected from the engine nozzle into the atmosphere), it would be a rather stiff task.<br>
<br>
Considerations similar to this absolutely permeate your design. (including, *~but not limited to~*: ...-neutron management from a 80 gigawatt(t) reactor in a 1 x 3 meter container. Both in maintaining a chain reaction of such high power with such short radii (reflectors would be in the wrong place), and the effect on structural material. ...-radiation coupling to fluids, ...-decay heat management, ...-multi-engine common mode failures (ie software or hardware glitch scramming multiple engines simultaneously or doing a hard-over gimble lock, ...-general thermal management, ...-actually achieving an Isp of +3000 in a lightbulb with your design, ...-lightbulb transparency across the ~entire~ spectrum including gamma rays, x-rays, UV, (plus some serious neutron and high velocity ion ablation), maintaining the required transparency thru-out the entire time period and avoiding compaction from the various fluxes, etc.)<br>
 <br>
In some ways, there appears to be a series of opacities  each running in the wrong direction. Maybe insufficient neutron &quot;opacity&quot; within the vortex to sustain reaction, excess opacity of the lightbulb to all frequencies and particles, insufficient opacity of the propellent, and excess opacity of the structure to &quot;waste&quot; particle fluxes (particularly neutrons and high energy photons)<br>
<br>
I have not posted in detail because I am working on some computer runs of energy transfer, etc in your engine.<br>
<br>
You will have to be patient. The rocket issue is lower priority.<br>
I am first creating posts for the &quot;energy on earth&quot; area where you posted data off by orders of magnitudes. It takes me a LONG time to develop a quality post.<br>
<br>
<br>
